    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/aTFoe.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1886487,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1705598,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1705598/icza",
                "reputation": 422929,
                "display_name": "icza",
                "accept_rate": 92
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1410504953,
            "creation_date": 1410504651,
            "body": "<p>If you only have like 50 elements, as noted in my comment, just sort it and take the last <code>k<\/code> elements. It's 2 lines only:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static double[] largests(double[] arr, int k) {\n    Arrays.sort(arr);\n    return Arrays.copyOfRange(arr, arr.length - k, arr.length);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This modifies (sorts) the original array. If you want your original array unmodified, you only need +1 line:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static double[] largests2(double[] arr, int k) {\n    arr = Arrays.copyOf(arr, arr.length);\n    Arrays.sort(arr);\n    return Arrays.copyOfRange(arr, arr.length - k, arr.length);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 25802415,
            "question_id": 25802052,
            "last_edit_date": 1410504953
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c7bdaca018a3f008ac133941a0d5e321?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 3068153,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2599416,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2599416/alexr",
                "reputation": 2428,
                "display_name": "AlexR"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1410506776,
            "creation_date": 1410504289,
            "body": "<p>You can use <code>System.arraycopy<\/code> on a sorted array:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>double[] getMaxElements(double[] input, int k) {\n    double[] temp = Arrays.copyOf(input, input.length);\n    Arrays.sort(temp); // Sort a copy to keep input as it is since Arrays.sort works in-place.\n    return Arrays.copyOfRange(temp, temp.length - k, temp.length); // Fetch largest elements\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>For 50 elements, it is much faster to sort an array than to mess with generics and comparables.<br>\nI will write up an additional \"fast\" algorithm...<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>double[] getMaxElements2(double[] input, int k) {\n    double[] res = new double[k];\n    for (int i = 0; i &lt; k; i++) res[i] = Double.NEGATIVE_INFINITY; // Make them as small as possible.\n    for (int j = 0; j &lt; input.length; j++) // Look at every element\n        if (res[0] &lt; input[j]) { // Keep the current element\n            res[0] = input[j];\n            Arrays.sort(res); // Keep the lowest kept element at res[0]\n        }\n    return res;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This is <code>O(N*k*log(k))<\/code> while the first one is <code>O(N*log(N))<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25802320,
            "question_id": 25802052,
            "last_edit_date": 1410506776
        }
    ],
